  <page>
    <title>Anthemius of Tralles</title>
    <id>1873</id>
    <revision>
      <id>430463755</id>
      <timestamp>2011-05-23T05:43:56Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <username>WereSpielChequers</username>
        <id>4071608</id>
      </contributor>
      <comment>added [[Category:6th-century deaths]] using [[WP:HC|HotCat]]</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">{{About||other people called &quot;Anthemius&quot;|Anthemius (disambiguation)}}
'''Anthemius of Tralles''' (c. 474 &amp;ndash; before 558; [[Greek language|Greek]]: {{Polytonic|Ἀνθέμιος ὁ Τραλλιανός}}) was a [[Greeks|Greek]] professor of [[Geometry]] in [[Constantinople]] (present-day [[Istanbul]] in Turkey) and [[architect]], who collaborated with [[Isidore of Miletus]] to build the church of [[Hagia Sophia]] by the order of [[Justinian I]]. Anthemius came from an educated family, one of five sons of Stephanus of [[Aydın|Tralles]], a physician. Of his brothers, Dioscorus followed his father's profession in Tralles; Alexander became at [[Rome]] one of the most celebrated medical men of his time; Olympius was deeply versed in [[Roman Law|Roman jurisprudence]]; and Metrodorus was a distinguished [[Philologist|grammarian]] in Constantinople.

As an architect he is best known for replacing the old church of [[Hagia Sophia]] at [[Constantinople]] in 532; his daring plans for the church strikingly displayed at once his knowledge and his ignorance. His skills seem also to have extended to engineering for he repaired the flood defences at [[Daras]].

Anthemius was also a capable mathematician. He described the string construction of the [[ellipse]]&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last=Boyer|authorlink=Carl Benjamin Boyer|title=|year=1991|chapter=Revival and Decline of Greek Mathematics|pages=193|quote=The commentary by Eutocius on the ''Conics'' of [[Apollonius]] was dedicated to Anthemius of Tralles (t534), an able mathematician and architect of St. Sophia of Constantinople, who described the string construction of the ellipse and wrote a work ''On Burning-mirrors'' in which the focal properties of the parabola are described.}} &lt;br /&gt;Although Anthemius died not 534 but before 558, cf. [[Oxford Dictionary of Byzantium]], p. 109.&lt;/ref&gt; and he wrote a book on [[conic section]]s, which was excellent preparation for designing the elaborate vaulting of Hagia Sophia. He compiled a survey of mirror configurations in his work on remarkable mechanical devices which was known to [[Islamic mathematics|Arab mathematicians]] such as [[Ibn al-Haytham]].

A fragment of his treatise ''On burning-glasses'' was published as ''{{polytonic|Περί παραδόξων μηχανημάτων}}'' (&quot;Concerning wondrous machines&quot;) by L. Dupuy in 1777, and also appeared in 1786 in the forty-second volume of the ''Histoire de l'Academie des Instrumentistes''. A. Westermann gave a revised edition of it in his ''{{polytonic|Παραδοξογράφοι}}'' (''Scriptores rerum mirabilium Graeci'', &quot;Greek marvel-writers&quot;) in 1839. In the course of the constructions for surfaces to reflect to one and the same point
# all rays in whatever direction passing through another point,
# a set of parallel rays,
Anthemius assumes a property of an ellipse not found in Apollonius work, that the equality of the angles subtended at a focus by two [[tangents]] drawn from a point, and having given the focus and a double ordinate he goes on to use the focus and [[directrix]] to obtain any number of points on a [[parabola]]&amp;mdash;the first instance on record of the practical use of the directrix.

