      <text xml:space="preserve">{{Infobox Constellation
| name = Ara
| abbreviation = Ara
| genitive = Arae
| pronounce = {{IPA-en|ˈɛərə|}}, genitive  {{IPA|/ˈɛəriː/}}&lt;ref&gt;Random House Dictionary&lt;/ref&gt;
| symbolism = the Altar
| RA = 17.39
| dec= −53.58
| family = [[Hercules Family|Hercules]]
| quadrant = SQ3
| areatotal = 237
| arearank = 63rd
| numbermainstars = 7
| numberbfstars = 17
| numberstarsplanets = 7
| numberbrightstars = 2
| numbernearbystars = 3
| brighteststarname = [[Beta Arae|β Ara]]
| starmagnitude = 2.84
| neareststarname = [[Gliese 674]]
| stardistancely = 14.80
| stardistancepc = 4.54
| numbermessierobjects = 0
| meteorshowers = None
| bordering = [[Corona Australis]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Scorpius]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Norma (constellation)|Norma]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Triangulum Australe]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Apus]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Pavo (constellation)|Pavo]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Telescopium]]
| latmax = [[25th parallel north|25]]
| latmin = [[South Pole|90]]
| month = July
| notes=}}
'''Ara''' is a southern [[constellation]] situated between [[Scorpius]] and [[Triangulum Australe]]. Its name is [[Latin]] for &quot;[[altar]]&quot;. Ara was one of the 48 Greek constellations described by the 2nd century astronomer [[Ptolemy]], and it remains one of the 88 modern constellations defined by the [[International Astronomical Union]].

==Notable features==
===Stars===
{{See also|List of stars in Ara}}
Ara's brightest star, [[Beta Arae|β Arae]], has an [[apparent magnitude]] of 2.9. [[Gamma Arae|γ Arae]] is a [[double star]] just south of β. [[Mu Arae|μ Arae]] is believed to have at least four planets orbiting it, one of which may be rocky in nature.{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}}

The constellation's stars have no names in [[Western culture]], but the [[Culture of China|Chinese]] call [[Alpha Arae|α Arae]] &quot;Choo&quot; (&quot;club&quot; or &quot;staff&quot;), and [[Epsilon Arae|ε Arae]] &quot;Tso Kang&quot;, meaning 'left guard'.{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}}

===Deep sky objects===
The northwest corner of Ara is crossed by the [[Milky Way]] and contains several [[open cluster]]s, notably [[NGC 6200]] and [[diffuse nebula]]e. The brightest of the [[globular cluster]]s, sixth magnitude [[NGC 6397]], at a distance of {{convert|8200|ly|km}} from our [[solar system]] might be the closest of all globular clusters in the sky.{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}}

====Open clusters====
*NGC 6193
*[[NGC 6200]]
*NGC 6204
*NGC 6208
*NGC 6250
*NGC 6253
*IC 4651

====Globular clusters====
*NGC 6352
*NGC 6362
*[[NGC 6397]]

The [[Stingray Nebula]] (Hen 3-1357), the youngest known planetary nebula as of 2010, formed in Ara; the light from its formation was first observable around 1987.

==Illustrations==
[[File:Ara Bode.jpg|thumb|left|[[Johann Elert Bode]]'s illustration of Ara, from his ''Uranographia'' (1801)]]
In illustrations, Ara is usually depicted as an [[altar]] with its smoke 'rising' southward.&lt;ref&gt;Ian Ridpath, [http://www.ianridpath.com/startales/ara.htm ''Star Tales''.]&lt;/ref&gt;

==Mythology==
In ancient [[Greek mythology]], Ara was identified as the altar, made by the [[Cyclops]], where the gods first made offerings and formed an alliance when they were about to fight the [[Titans]].&lt;ref name=&quot;hyginus.astronomica.39&quot;&gt;[[Hyginus]], ''Astronomica'', 39, ''Altar''&lt;/ref&gt;

==Equivalents==
In [[Chinese astronomy]], the stars of the constellation Ara lie within ''[[Azure Dragon|The Azure Dragon of the East]]'' (東方青龍, ''Dōng Fāng Qīng Lóng'').&lt;ref&gt;{{zh icon}} [http://aeea.nmns.edu.tw/2006/0607/ap060701.html AEEA (Activities of Exhibition and Education in Astronomy) 天文教育資訊網 2006 年 7 月 1 日]&lt;/ref&gt;

==Namesakes==
[[USS Ara (AK-136)]] was a [[United States]] navy ship.

==See also==
[[Ara in Chinese astronomy]]

