'''Apus''' is a faint [[constellation]] in the southern sky, first defined in the late 16th century. Its name means &quot;no feet&quot; in [[Greek language|Greek]], and it represents a [[bird-of-paradise]] (which were once believed to lack feet). It is bordered by [[Triangulum Australe]], [[Circinus]], [[Musca]], [[Chamaeleon]], [[Octans]], [[Pavo (constellation)|Pavo]] and [[Ara (constellation)|Ara]]. Its [[genitive]] is &quot;Apodis&quot;.

==History==
Apus was one of twelve constellations created by [[Petrus Plancius]] from the observations of [[Pieter Dirkszoon Keyser]] and [[Frederick de Houtman]] and it first appeared on a 35&amp;nbsp;cm diameter celestial globe published in 1597 (or 1598) in Amsterdam by Plancius with [[Jodocus Hondius]]. Plancius called the constellation '''Paradysvogel Apis Indica'''; the first word is [[Dutch language|Dutch]] for 'bird of paradise', but the others are [[Latin]] for &quot;Indian Bee&quot;; &quot;apis&quot; (Latin for &quot;bee&quot;) is presumably an error for &quot;avis&quot; or &quot;bird&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ianridpath.com/startales/apus.htm]&lt;/ref&gt; This confusion seems to have prompted a rename of two constellations: &quot;Avis Indica&quot; to &quot;Apus&quot; and the constellation of the bee, Apis, to [[Musca]] the fly.{{Citation needed|date=November 2008}}

After its introduction on Plancius's globe, the first known depiction of the constellation in a celestial atlas was in [[Johann Bayer]]'s ''[[Uranometria]]'' of 1603.

== Notable features ==
{{See also|List of stars in Apus}}
Apus includes two impressive clusters, [[NGC 6101]] and [[IC 4499]], as well as a very unusual nebular structure [[IC 4633]].

==Equivalents==
When the [[Ming Dynasty]] Chinese astronomer [[Xu Guangqi]] adapted the European southern hemisphere constellations to the Chinese system in ''[[Chinese constellations#The Southern Asterisms|The Southern Asterisms]]'', he combined Apus with some of the stars in [[Octans]] to form the &quot;[[Chinese constellations#The Southern Asterisms|Exotic Bird]]&quot; (異雀, ''Yìquè'').&lt;ref&gt;{{zh icon}} [http://aeea.nmns.edu.tw/2006/0607/ap060729.html AEEA (Activities of Exhibition and Education in Astronomy) 天文教育資訊網 2006 年 7 月 29 日]&lt;/ref&gt;

